[49m[39m  552, 552[0m:[39m[49m **Where It Struggles:**
[0m[49m[39m  553, 553[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 554     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - **Mass casualty events:** The model assumes normal arrival patterns. A sudden influx of 20+ patients overwhelms the optimization (too many assignments, too few beds, constraints become infeasible). You need a separate surge protocol that bypasses normal optimization.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 555     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - **Behavioral health patients:** Placement constraints are complex and often undocumented (elopement risk, self-harm precautions, specific room configurations). The model frequently gets overridden for these patients.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 556     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - **"Soft" bed blocks:** Some hospitals informally reserve beds for specific services ("those two beds are always for cardiology"). These aren't in any system but staff enforce them. The optimizer doesn't know about them and gets overridden.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 557     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m - **Discharge prediction uncertainty:** If your predicted discharge time is wrong by 2 hours, beds you planned on aren't available when you need them. The optimization is only as good as the discharge predictions feeding it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Mass casualty events:** The model assumes normal arrival patterns. A sudden influx of 20+ patients overwhelms the optimization (too many assignments, too few beds, constraints become infeasible). Don't try to optimize during a surge. Just place people safely and sort it out later. You need a separate surge protocol that bypasses normal optimization entirely.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Behavioral health patients:** Placement constraints are complex and often undocumented (elopement risk, self-harm precautions, specific room configurations). We've seen 60%+ override rates for behavioral health placements. The model just doesn't have the context that experienced staff carry in their heads.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **"Soft" bed blocks:** Some hospitals informally reserve beds for specific services ("those two beds are always for cardiology"). These aren't in any system but staff enforce them religiously. The optimizer doesn't know about them and gets overridden, and you'll spend weeks tracking down why acceptance rates are low on certain units.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Discharge prediction uncertainty:** If your predicted discharge time is wrong by 2 hours, beds you planned on aren't available when you need them. The optimization is only as good as the discharge predictions feeding it, and those predictions are often optimistic.
